===Etymology 1===
{{etyl|ang}} {{term|lifer|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|librō|lang=gem-pro}}. Cognate with Dutch {{term|lever|lang=nl}}, German {{term|Leber}}, Danish, Norwegian and Swedish {{term|lever}} (the last three from Old Norse {{term|lifr|lang=non}}).

====Pronunciation====
* {{IPA|lɪvə(r)|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-liver.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|ɪvə(r)}}

====Noun====
{{en-noun|s|-}}

# {{anatomy}} A large [[organ]] in the body that stores and [[metabolize]]s [[nutrient]]s, destroys [[toxins]] and produces [[bile]]. It is responsible for thousands of [[biochemical]] [[chemical reaction|reaction]]s.
#: ''Steve Jobs is a famous '''liver''' transplant recipient.''
# {{countable|uncountable}} This organ, as taken from animals used as food.
#: ''I'd like some goose '''liver''' pate.''
#: ''You could fry up some chicken '''livers''' for a tasty treat. — Nah, I don't like chicken '''liver'''.''
#* '''1993''', Philippa Gregory, ''Fallen Skies'', ISBN-13: 978-1-4165-9314-0, page 222:
#*: "I should think you've rocked the boat enough already by refusing to eat '''liver'''."
# A dark brown colour, tinted with red and gray, like the colour of liver.
#: {{color panel|674C47}}

=====Usage notes=====
* The noun is often used attributively to modify other words. Used in this way, it frequently means "concerning the liver"<!-- French: de [[foie]]; Italian: di [[fegato]]-->, "intended for the liver" <!-- French: [[pour]] le [[foie]]; Italian: per il [[fegato]] --> or "made of liver" <!-- French: de [[foie]]; Italian: di fegato -->.

